<p>In the latest development in northern Syria, government forces pushed deeper into Kurdish-held areas, taking Tabqa and its dam as they moved toward Raqqa, a city long overseen by the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF). The United States publicly urged restraint and de-escalation amid fears the fighting could widen, even as it maintains ties with both the SDF and Syria’s new authorities. The SDF said Syrian forces violated a withdrawal understanding, while Syrian state media reported territorial gains and accused the SDF of attacking an army patrol during the pullback.</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/SMtm0yfSwwHQ23CMlENf2n1TG5Emhr1NBYDRSfF57Ny2Mlsna3Oi2LN-CHRaY8jyiSyLyz7bK3bzuSElEaZ49pJbf4ktBAjsahe31wKJ' alt='Erbil: Massoud Barzani and SDF leader Mazloum Abdi meet US Special Envoy Tom Barrack in Iraq.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Language decree: President Ahmed al‑Sharaa issued a decree declaring Kurdish a “national language” and granting official recognition to the minority, which Kurdish officials described as a goodwill step that still falls short of their aspirations.</li><li>Villages and airport: Syrian state media said the army took dozens of locations east of Aleppo, including Deir Hafer and Maskana, and also took control of a military airport during the advance.</li><li>Oilfields seized: Syrian forces also seized the Sufyan and Thawrah oil fields in northern Syria as SDF units withdrew from multiple towns under the deal.</li><li>Mediator meetings: US envoy Tom Barrack met SDF leader Mazloum Abdi in Erbil, alongside Iraqi Kurdish leader Massoud Barzani, as Washington sought to encourage de-escalation and manage ties across the different Syrian actors.</li><li>Civilian returns: A Dawn reporter in Deir Hafer described residents returning after earlier displacement as SDF fighters departed under heavy security presence, offering a small sign of day-to-day life resuming in at least one contested area.</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>United States government: Washington urged restraint and de-escalation as Syrian troops moved toward Kurdish-held areas, citing concern about a renewed wider conflict, while keeping relationships with both the SDF and Syria’s new authorities. (<a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/17/world/middleeast/syrian-kurds-raqqa.html'>The New York Times</a>)</li><li>Syrian government/army: Syrian state media and the army described the operation as securing towns, infrastructure, and the withdrawal of SDF fighters and weapons, while also accusing the SDF of violating the agreement and attacking an army patrol near Maskana. (<a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1967588/damascus-takes-control-of-more-territory-seizes-two-oil-fields'>Dawn</a>)</li><li>Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF): The SDF said Syrian forces violated a withdrawal deal even as SDF leadership indicated it would redeploy forces east of the Euphrates after calls from mediators and “friendly countries.”. (<a href='https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2026/1/17/us-urges-de-escalation-as-syrian-army-advances-on-kurdish-territory'>Al Jazeera</a>)</li><li>Kurdish political view (as reported): Some Kurdish voices portrayed the army’s move into Kurdish-held towns as a “betrayal” that could damage chances of reaching an accommodation to fold Kurdish forces into a national structure. (<a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/jan/18/syrian-army-surges-into-kurdish-held-towns-in-betrayal-shattering-hopes-of-accord'>The Guardian</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.nytimes.com/2026/01/17/world/middleeast/syrian-kurds-raqqa.html'>Syria Advance on Kurdish-Held Areas as Washington Urges Restraint</a> - nytimes.com</li><li><a href='https://www.dawn.com/news/1967588/damascus-takes-control-of-more-territory-seizes-two-oil-fields'>Damascus takes control of more territory, seizes two oil fields</a> - dawn.com</li><li><a href='https://www.theguardian.com/world/2026/jan/18/syrian-army-surges-into-kurdish-held-